data_gen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1.0/255)

img_size = 128
batch_size = 48

def data_generator(dir, data_gen):
    generator = data_gen.flow_from_directory(
        dir,
        target_size=(img_size, img_size),
        batch_size=batch_size,
        class_mode='binary',
        classes=['other', 'car'],
        seed=12345,
        shuffle=True)
    return generator

train_generator = data_generator('train', data_gen)
val_generator = data_generator('validation', data_gen)

Make convolutional net function :)

In [5]:
def make_convnet(img_width=64, img_height=64, channels=3):
    """
    Creates a convolutional neural network with the specified input shape.
    For binary classification.
    """
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(5, 5), strides=(1, 1),
                    activation='relu',
                    input_shape=(img_width, img_height, 3)))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), strides=(2, 2)))
    model.add(Conv2D(64, (5, 5), activation='relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy',
                optimizer='adam',
                metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

Make function for displaying history :)

In [6]:
def display_history(history):
    try:
        history = history.history
    except:
        pass
    fig = plt.figure()
    plt.plot(history['loss'], color='teal', label='loss')
    plt.plot(history['val_loss'], color='orange', label='val_loss')
    fig.suptitle('Loss', fontsize=20)
    plt.legend(loc="upper left")
    plt.show()

    fig = plt.figure()
    plt.plot(history['accuracy'], color='teal', label='accuracy')
    plt.plot(history['val_accuracy'], color='orange', label='val_accuracy')
    fig.suptitle('Accuracy', fontsize=20)
    plt.legend(loc="upper left")
    plt.show()

Part 2: Data Augmentation¶

We used the same code as in Part 1 but with added augmentation in ImageDataGenerator. The augmentation was carefully chosen to not change the images too much. We assume for example that the majority of the images of cars are not upside down. Therefore we do not invert along the X-axis or rotate in any direction more than 30 degrees. We also do not change the brightness or zoom in or out. We do however shift the image in the X and Y direction and flip the image along the Y-axis. This is to make the model more robust to changes in the position of the car in the image.

In [11]:
data_gen_aug = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1.0/255,
                             horizontal_flip=True,
                             brightness_range=[0.5, 1.5],
                             zoom_range=[0.8, 1.2],
                             rotation_range=35,
                             channel_shift_range=10.0,
                             data_format='channels_last'
                             )

def get_labels(n):
    return np.array([0]*(n//2) + [1]*(n//2))

Our Neural network to train on the cnn_features

In [20]:
def train_on_cnnfeatures():
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Flatten(input_shape=cnn_features_train.shape[1:]))
    model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.5))
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy',
                optimizer='adam',
                metrics=['accuracy'])
                
    with open('predict.pred', 'rb') as f: cnn_features = np.load(f)

    hist = model.fit(cnn_features,
                    get_labels(cnn_features.shape[0]),
                    epochs=epochs,
                    batch_size=batch_size,
                    validation_data=(cnn_features_val, get_labels(cnn_features_val.shape[0])))

    return hist

In [23]:
def kernel_image(weights, i, positive):
    
    # extract the convolutional kernel at position i
    k = weights[:,:,:,i].copy()
    if not positive:
        k = -k
    
    # clip the values: if we're looking for positive
    # values, just keep the positive part; vice versa
    # for the negative values.
    k *= k > 0

    # rescale the colors, to make the images less dark
    m = k.max()
    if m > 1e-3:
        k /= m 

    return k

    img = kernel_image(first_layer_weights, i, True)

Conclusion¶

We conclude that with our parameters (image size = 128x128, batch size = 34) we can se that the normal CNN using unagumented data peaks at about five epochs of training at an accuracy of about 75%. The model training on agumented data can reach higher at about 80% when training for many more epochs and it seems to peak at about 30 epochs, until it starts to get overfitted. At the start it is worse, but when training it alot on many different agumented images it improves and ourperforms the normal model. The feature extraction model starts strong and does not improve alot with each epoch, it seems to peak even before five epochs of traning and gets an accuracy of about 90%. We take note that feature extraction is a very good way to recognize features and thus improving performance of our models. We also note that there are other ways of doing image recognition rather than creating your own models, as there are very good ones out there in places like keras for example. The one shown to us reached a straggeringly high accuracy in identifying the pot in the image, which was impressive, as it has so many objects it can detect.
